title:	SELECT/WHEN without OTHERWISE fails with 'CODEGEN ERROR: unsupported statement kind'
state:	CLOSED
author:	softwarewrighter (Software Wrighter LLC)
labels:	bug
comments:	2
assignees:	
projects:	
milestone:	
number:	34
--
## Problem
A SELECT statement without an OTHERWISE clause fails to compile with "CODEGEN ERROR: unsupported statement kind". Adding an OTHERWISE clause makes the same code compile fine.

## Reproduction

**Fails:**
```
DCL X INT STATIC INIT(5);

MAIN: PROC;
    SELECT;
        WHEN (X = 3) CALL UART_PUTCHAR(65);
        WHEN (X = 5) CALL UART_PUTCHAR(66);
    END;
END;
```

Output:
```
CODEGEN ERROR: unsupported statement kind
--- compilation failed ---
```

**Compiles fine (only difference is added OTHERWISE):**
```
DCL X INT STATIC INIT(5);

MAIN: PROC;
    SELECT;
        WHEN (X = 3) CALL UART_PUTCHAR(65);
        WHEN (X = 5) CALL UART_PUTCHAR(66);
        OTHERWISE CALL UART_PUTCHAR(63);
    END;
END;
```

## Expected behavior
OTHERWISE should be optional (this matches PL/I semantics — omitting OTHERWISE means "fall through with no action when no WHEN matches"). The compiler should either:
1. Treat missing OTHERWISE as an implicit no-op, or
2. Emit a clear error message saying OTHERWISE is required, not a "CODEGEN ERROR: unsupported statement kind".

## Impact
Forces every SELECT statement to include `OTHERWISE DO; END;` boilerplate, which is verbose and easy to forget. The error message also obscures the real cause.

## Workaround
Add `OTHERWISE DO; END;` (or any OTHERWISE clause) to every SELECT block.

