gh issue comment 33 --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
Investigated and decided to document this as a known limitation rather than attempt a fix, since there's a clean workaround.

## Root cause

Both the parser (`parse_stmt` → IF branch in `src/parser.h`) and the code generator (`cg_if` in `src/codegen.h`) handle `IF / ELSE IF` as right-nested recursion: each `ELSE IF` becomes another nested `NODE_IF` in the parent's else branch, and each level adds a C call frame. Since the PL/SW compiler itself runs on COR24 with an 8 KB EBR stack, a chain of ~90+ branches exhausts the host compiler's stack during parse or codegen. The compiler either resets (restarting the main menu loop) or runs to the cycle limit with no error — which matches the reported symptoms.

Converting `parse_stmt`/`cg_if` to iterate over an ELSE-IF spine instead of recursing is feasible but nontrivial, and the workaround below is clean enough that the fix isn't pressing.

## Workaround — use `SELECT / WHEN`

`SELECT` is the right construct for long dispatch chains. Unlike IF/ELSE-IF, `cg_select` iterates `WHEN` children in a loop inside a single frame, so it has no practical limit on the number of branches.

```plsw
SELECT;
    WHEN (OP = 1) CALL DO_ADD();
    WHEN (OP = 2) CALL DO_SUB();
    /* ...hundreds more WHEN clauses are fine... */
    OTHERWISE CALL BAD_OPCODE();
END;
```

`OTHERWISE` is optional (as of b63ab15 / issue #34).

## Documentation

Added a "Known Limitations" section to `docs/usage.md` covering this limitation and pointing users at `SELECT / WHEN` for dispatch-style code.

Leaving this issue open as a tracking ticket in case we decide to rewrite the IF codegen iteratively later. Feel free to close if you'd rather track it elsewhere.
EOF
)"

